33\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 The skin of a sheep, goat, or calf prepared for use as writing material. It was more durable than papyrus and was used for scrolls of the Bible. The parchments that Paul requested Timothy to bring were possibly portions of the Hebrew Scriptures. Some of the Dead Sea Scrolls were written on parchment.\u8212?}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf4 2 Timothy 4}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 :13.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ab\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\b Party followers of Herod.}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 \u8212?See Herod; party followers of.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ab\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\b Passover. }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 An annual festival observed on the 14th day of Abib (later called Nisan) to commemorate the deliverance of the Israelites from Egypt. It was observed by slaughtering and roasting a lamb (or goat), which was then eaten with bitter greens and unleavened bread.\u8212?}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf4 Exodus 1}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 2:27; }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf4 John 6}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 :4; }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\cf4 1 Corinthians 5}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2 :7.\par}{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ab\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\f2\b Pentecost. }{\rtlch\fcs1\alang1033\af1\ltrch\fcs0\lang1033\langnp1033\la